<p>The SI comprises a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coherence_(u=
nits_of_measurement)" title=3D"Coherence (units of measurement)">coherent</=
a> system of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_of_measurement" =
title=3D"Unit of measurement">units of measurement</a> starting with seven =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_base_unit" title=3D"SI base uni=
t">base units</a>, which are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
econd" title=3D"Second">second</a> (symbol s, the unit of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time" title=3D"Time">time</a>), <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre" title=3D"Metre">metre</a> (m, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Length" title=3D"Length">length</a>), <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilogram" title=3D"Kilogram">kilogram</a> (kg,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass" title=3D"Mass">mass</a>), <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ampere" title=3D"Ampere">ampere</a>=
 (A, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_current" title=3D"El=
ectric current">electric current</a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Kelvin" title=3D"Kelvin">kelvin</a> (K, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Thermodynamic_temperature" title=3D"Thermodynamic temperature">t=
hermodynamic temperature</a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mol=
e_(unit)" title=3D"Mole (unit)">mole</a> (mol, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Amount_of_substance" title=3D"Amount of substance">amount of s=
ubstance</a>), and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Candela" title=
=3D"Candela">candela</a> (cd, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lumi=
nous_intensity" title=3D"Luminous intensity">luminous intensity</a>). The s=
ystem can accommodate coherent units for an unlimited number of additional =
quantities. These are called coherent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/SI_derived_unit" title=3D"SI derived unit">derived units</a>, which can=
 always be represented as products of powers of the base units. Twenty-two =
coherent derived units have been provided with special names and symbols.
</p><p>The seven base units and the 22 coherent derived units with special =
names and symbols may be used in combination to express other coherent deri=
ved units. Since the sizes of coherent units will be convenient for only so=
me applications and not for others, the SI provides twenty-four <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_prefix" title=3D"Metric prefix">prefix=
es</a> which, when added to the name and symbol of a coherent unit produce =
twenty-four additional (non-coherent) SI units for the same quantity; these=
 non-coherent units are always decimal (i.e. power-of-ten) multiples and su=
b-multiples of the coherent unit.
</p><p>The current way of defining the SI is a result of a decades-long mov=
e towards increasingly abstract and idealised formulation in which the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Realisation_(metrology)" title=3D"Real=
isation (metrology)">realisations</a> of the units are separated conceptual=
ly from the definitions. A consequence is that as science and technologies =
develop, new and superior realisations may be introduced without the need t=
o redefine the unit. One problem with artefacts is that they can be lost, d=
amaged, or changed; another is that they introduce uncertainties that canno=
t be reduced by advancements in science and technology.
</p><p>The original motivation for the development of the SI was the divers=
ity of units that had sprung up within the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Centimetre%E2%80%93gram%E2%80%93second_system_of_units" title=3D"C=
entimetre=E2=80=93gram=E2=80=93second system of units">centimetre=E2=80=93g=
ram=E2=80=93second</a> (CGS) systems (specifically the inconsistency betwee=
n the systems of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrostatic_uni=
ts" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electrostatic units">electrostatic units=
</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetic_units" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electromagnetic units">electromagnetic units</=
a>) and the lack of coordination between the various <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Discipline_(academia)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Di=
scipline (academia)">disciplines</a> that used them. The General Conference=
 on Weights and Measures (French: <i><span title=3D"French-language text"><=
i lang=3D"fr">Conf=C3=A9rence g=C3=A9n=C3=A9rale des poids et mesures</i></=
span></i> =E2=80=93 CGPM), which was established by the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre_Convention" title=3D"Metre Convention">Metre Co=
nvention</a> of 1875, brought together many international organisations to =
establish the definitions and standards of a new system and to standardise =
the rules for writing and presenting measurements. The system was published=
 in 1960 as a result of an initiative that began in 1948, and is based on t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MKS_system_of_units" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"MKS system of units">metre=E2=80=93kilogram=E2=80=93se=
cond system of units</a> (MKS) combined with ideas from the development of =
the CGS system.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInternational_Sy=
stem_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Def=
inition"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>The International System of Units consists of a set of seven defining co=
nstants with seven corresponding base units, derived units, and a set of de=
cimal-based multipliers that are used as prefixes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBro=
chure9thEd_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 125">:=E2=80=8A125=E2=80=
=8A</span></sup>
</p>
