<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Derived_units">Derived unit=
s</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInternatio=
nal_System_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Derived units"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_derived_unit" tit=
le=3D"SI derived unit">SI derived unit</a></div>
<p>The system allows for an unlimited number of additional units, called <i=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_derived_unit" title=3D"SI deri=
ved unit">derived units</a></i>, which can always be represented as product=
s of powers of the base units, possibly with a nontrivial numeric multiplie=
r. When that multiplier is one, the unit is called a <i><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coherence_(units_of_measurement)" title=3D"Coherence =
(units of measurement)">coherent</a></i> derived unit. For example, the coh=
erent derived SI unit of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Velocity"=
 title=3D"Velocity">velocity</a> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Metre_per_second" title=3D"Metre per second">metre per second</a>, wi=
th the symbol <span class=3D"nowrap">m/s</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBroch=
ure9thEd_1-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup c=
lass=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 139">:=E2=80=8A139=E2=80=8A<=
/span></sup> The base and coherent derived units of the SI together form a =
coherent system of units (<i>the set of coherent SI units</i>). A useful pr=
operty of a coherent system is that when the numerical values of physical q=
uantities are expressed in terms of the units of the system, then the equat=
ions between the numerical values have exactly the same form, including num=
erical factors, as the corresponding equations between the physical quantit=
ies.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ISO80000-1_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-ISO80000-=
1-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 6">:=E2=
=80=8A6=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>Twenty-two coherent derived units have been provided with special na=
mes and symbols as shown in the table below. The radian and steradian have =
no base units but are treated as derived units for historical reasons.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9th=
Ed-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 137">:=
=E2=80=8A137=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
