<div style=3D"clear:both;" class=3D""></div>
<p>The derived units in the SI are formed by powers, products, or quotients=
 of the base units and are unlimited in number.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochu=
re9thEd_1-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup c=
lass=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 138">:=E2=80=8A138=E2=80=8A<=
/span></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST330_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-NIST=
330-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 14, =
16">:=E2=80=8A14,=E2=80=8A16=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Physics_measurements_SI_units.png" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/e/e6/Physics_measurements_SI_units.png/250px-Physics_measurements=
_SI_units.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"338" class=3D"mw-=
file-element" data-file-width=3D"494" data-file-height=3D"667"></a><figcapt=
ion>Arrangement of the principal measurements in physics based on the mathe=
matical manipulation of length, time, and mass</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derived_unit" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Derived unit">Derived units</a> apply to some <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derived_quantity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Derived quantity">derived quantities</a>, which may by definition be expres=
sed in terms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_quantity" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Base quantity">base quantities</a>, and thus ar=
e not independent; for example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El=
ectrical_conductance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electrical conductance=
">electrical conductance</a> is the inverse of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Electrical_resistance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electric=
al resistance">electrical resistance</a>, with the consequence that the sie=
mens is the inverse of the ohm, and similarly, the ohm and siemens can be r=
eplaced with a ratio of an ampere and a volt, because those quantities bear=
 a defined relationship to each other.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Uni=
ts#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other useful derived quantities can be specifie=
d in terms of the SI base and derived units that have no named units in the=
 SI, such as acceleration, which has the SI unit m/s<sup>2</sup>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 139">:=E2=
=80=8A139=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>A combination of base and derived units may be used to express a der=
ived unit. For example, the SI unit of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Force" title=3D"Force">force</a> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Newton_(unit)" title=3D"Newton (unit)">newton</a> (N), the SI un=
it of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pressure" title=3D"Pressure"=
>pressure</a> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pascal_(unit)=
" title=3D"Pascal (unit)">pascal</a> (Pa) =E2=80=93 and the pascal can be d=
efined as one newton per square metre (N/m<sup>2</sup>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internati=
onal_System_of_Units#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Prefixes">Prefixes</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInternational_System=
_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Prefixe=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_prefix" title=
=3D"Metric prefix">Metric prefix</a></div>
<p>Like all metric systems, the SI uses <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Metric_prefix" title=3D"Metric prefix">metric prefixes</a> to systema=
tically construct, for the same physical quantity, a set of units that are =
decimal multiples of each other over a wide range. For example, driving dis=
tances are normally given in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilom=
etre" title=3D"Kilometre">kilometres</a> (symbol <span class=3D"nowrap">km<=
/span>) rather than in metres. Here the metric prefix '<a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilo-" title=3D"Kilo-">kilo-</a>' (symbol 'k') stands =
for a factor of 1000; thus, <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D=
"7003100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1&nbsp;km</span> =3D <span class=3D"n=
owrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7003100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1000&n=
bsp;m</span>.
</p><p>The SI provides twenty-four metric prefixes that signify decimal pow=
ers ranging from 10<sup>=E2=88=9230</sup> to 10<sup>30</sup>, the most rece=
nt being adopted in 2022.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-12" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_o=
f_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowr=
ap"><span title=3D"Pages: 143=E2=80=93144">:=E2=80=8A143=E2=80=93144=E2=80=
=8A</span></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-12"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Most prefixes co=
rrespond to integer powers of 1000; the only ones that do not are those for=
 10, 1/10, 100, and 1/100.
The conversion between different SI units for one and the same physical qua=
ntity is always through a power of ten. This is why the SI (and metric syst=
ems more generally) are called <i>decimal systems of measurement units</i>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DecimalSystem_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-DecimalSy=
stem-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Compound_unit"></span>The grouping form=
ed by a prefix symbol attached to a unit symbol (e.g. '<span class=3D"nowra=
p">km</span>', '<span class=3D"nowrap">cm</span>') constitutes a new insepa=
rable unit symbol. This new symbol can be raised to a positive or negative =
power. It can also be combined with other unit symbols to form <i>compound =
unit</i> symbols.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-13" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#=
cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><spa=
n title=3D"Page: 143">:=E2=80=8A143=E2=80=8A</span></sup> For example, <spa=
n class=3D"nowrap">g/cm<sup>3</sup></span> is an SI unit of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Density" title=3D"Density">density</a>, where <sp=
an class=3D"nowrap">cm<sup>3</sup></span> is to be interpreted as (<span cl=
ass=3D"nowrap">cm</span>)<sup>3</sup>.
</p><p>Prefixes are added to unit names to produce multiples and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Submultiple" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Submultiple">submultiples</a> of the original unit. All of these are intege=
r powers of ten, and above a hundred or below a hundredth all are integer p=
owers of a thousand. For example, <i>kilo-</i> denotes a multiple of a thou=
sand and <i>milli-</i> denotes a multiple of a thousandth, so there are one=
 thousand millimetres to the metre and one thousand metres to the kilometre=
. The prefixes are never combined, so for example a millionth of a metre is=
 a <i>micrometre</i>, not a <i>millimillimetre</i>. Multiples of the kilogr=
am are named as if the gram were the base unit, so a millionth of a kilogra=
m is a <i>milligram</i>, not a <i>microkilogram</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIB=
rochure_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure-16"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup clas=
s=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 122">:=E2=80=8A122=E2=80=8A</sp=
an></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST811_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-NIST81=
1-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 14">:=
=E2=80=8A14=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>The BIPM specifies 24 prefixes for the International System of Units=
 (SI):
