<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Coherent_and_non-coherent_S=
I_units">Coherent and non-coherent SI units <span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Co=
herent_SI_units"></span></h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index=
.php?title=3DInternational_System_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
6" title=3D"Edit section: Coherent and non-coherent SI units"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coherent_unit=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coherent unit">Coherent unit</a></div>
<p>The base units and the derived units formed as the product of powers of =
the base units with a numerical factor of one form a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Coherent_system_of_units" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Coherent system of units">coherent system of units</a>. Every physical qua=
ntity has exactly one coherent SI unit. For example, <span class=3D"nowrap"=
>1 m/s =3D (1 m) / (1 s)</span> is the coherent derived unit for velocity.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochu=
re9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 1=
39">:=E2=80=8A139=E2=80=8A</span></sup> With the exception of the kilogram =
(for which the prefix kilo- is required for a coherent unit), when prefixes=
 are used with the coherent SI units, the resulting units are no longer coh=
erent, because the prefix introduces a numerical factor other than one.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9=
thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 137"=
>:=E2=80=8A137=E2=80=8A</span></sup> For example, the metre, kilometre, cen=
timetre, nanometre, etc. are all SI units of length, though only the metre =
is a <em>coherent</em> SI unit. The complete set of SI units consists of bo=
th the coherent set and the multiples and sub-multiples of coherent units f=
ormed by using the SI prefixes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-16" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Sy=
stem_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"referenc=
e nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 138">:=E2=80=8A138=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>The kilogram is the only coherent SI unit whose name and symbol incl=
ude a prefix. For historical reasons, the names and symbols for multiples a=
nd sub-multiples of the unit of mass are formed as if the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gram" title=3D"Gram">gram</a> were the base unit. P=
refix names and symbols are attached to the unit name <i>gram</i> and the u=
nit symbol g respectively. For example, <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-s=
ort-value=3D"6994100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>=E2=88=926</sup>&n=
bsp;kg</span> is written <i>milligram</i> and <span class=3D"nowrap">mg</sp=
an>, not <i>microkilogram</i> and <span class=3D"nowrap">=CE=BCkg</span>.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochur=
e9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 14=
4">:=E2=80=8A144=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>Several different quantities may share the same coherent SI unit. Fo=
r example, the joule per kelvin (symbol <span class=3D"nowrap">J/K</span>) =
is the coherent SI unit for two distinct quantities: <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Heat_capacity" title=3D"Heat capacity">heat capacity</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entropy" title=3D"Entropy">en=
tropy</a>; another example is the ampere, which is the coherent SI unit for=
 both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_current" title=3D"E=
lectric current">electric current</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Magnetomotive_force" title=3D"Magnetomotive force">magnetomotive fo=
rce</a>. This illustrates why it is important not to use the unit alone to =
specify the quantity. As the <i>SI Brochure</i> states,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
SIBrochure9thEd_1-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 140">:=E2=80=8A140=
=E2=80=8A</span></sup> "this applies not only to technical texts, but also,=
 for example, to measuring instruments (i.e. the instrument read-out needs =
to indicate both the unit and the quantity measured)".
</p><p>Furthermore, the same coherent SI unit may be a base unit in one con=
text, but a coherent derived unit in another. For example, the ampere is a =
base unit when it is a unit of electric current, but a coherent derived uni=
t when it is a unit of magnetomotive force.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9t=
hEd_1-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inte=
rnational_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=
=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 140">:=E2=80=8A140=E2=80=8A</spa=
n></sup>
</p>
