<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Lexicographic_conventions">=
Lexicographic conventions <span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"SI_writing_style"></=
span></h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntern=
ational_System_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Lexicographic conventions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_31-0#Typographic_con=
ventions" title=3D"ISO 31-0">ISO 31-0 =C2=A7&nbsp;Typographic conventions</=
a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_(punctuation)#Unit_s=
ymbols_and_numbers" title=3D"Space (punctuation)">Space (punctuation) =C2=
=A7&nbsp;Unit symbols and numbers</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:981ms2.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><im=
g src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0c/981ms2.png" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"200" height=3D"85" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"200" data-file-height=3D"85"></a><figcaption>Example of lexi=
cal conventions. In the expression of acceleration due to gravity, a space =
separates the value and the units, both the 'm' and the 's' are lowercase b=
ecause neither the metre nor the second are named after people, and exponen=
tiation is represented with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supe=
rscript" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Superscript">superscript</a> '2'.</=
figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Unit_names">Unit names</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInternational_Sy=
stem_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Uni=
t names"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>According to the SI Brochure,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-20" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_S=
ystem_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"referen=
ce nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 148">:=E2=80=8A148=E2=80=8A</span></sup> un=
it names should be treated as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comm=
on_noun" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Common noun">common nouns</a> of th=
e context language. This means that they should be typeset in the same char=
acter set as other common nouns (e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Latin_alphabet" title=3D"Latin alphabet">Latin alphabet</a> in English,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyrillic_script" title=3D"Cyrilli=
c script">Cyrillic script</a> in Russian, etc.), following the usual gramma=
tical and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthography" title=3D"Or=
thography">orthographical</a> rules of the context language. For example, i=
n English and French, even when the unit is named after a person and its sy=
mbol begins with a capital letter, the unit name in running text should sta=
rt with a lowercase letter (e.g., newton, hertz, pascal) and is <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capitalised" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"C=
apitalised">capitalised</a> only at the beginning of a sentence and in <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Title_capitalization" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Title capitalization">headings and publication titles</a>. A=
s a nontrivial application of this rule, the SI Brochure notes<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 148">:=E2=80=
=8A148=E2=80=8A</span></sup> that the name of the unit with the symbol <spa=
n class=3D"nowrap">=C2=B0C</span> is correctly spelled as 'degree <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celsius" title=3D"Celsius">Celsius</a>': =
the first letter of the name of the unit, 'd', is in lowercase, while the m=
odifier 'Celsius' is capitalised because it is a proper name.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 148">:=E2=80=
=8A148=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>The English spelling and even names for certain SI units, prefixes a=
nd non-SI units depend on the variety of English used. <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_English" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"US English"=
>US English</a> uses the spelling <i>deka-</i>, <i>meter</i>, and <i>liter<=
/i>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_English" ti=
tle=3D"International English">International English</a> uses <i>deca-</i>, =
<i>metre</i>, and <i>litre</i>. The name of the unit whose symbol is t and =
which is defined by <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7003100=
000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1&nbsp;t</span> =3D <span class=3D"nowrap"><s=
pan data-sort-value=3D"7003100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>3</sup>&=
nbsp;kg</span> is 'metric ton' in US English and 'tonne' in International E=
nglish.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST330_9-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-NIST330-9=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: iii">:=E2=
=80=8Aiii=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Unit_symbols_and_the_values=
_of_quantities">Unit symbols and the values of quantities</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInternational_System_of_Un=
its&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Unit symbols =
and the values of quantities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Symbols of SI units are intended to be unique and universal, independent=
 of the context language.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure_16-1" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Uni=
ts#cite_note-SIBrochure-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><spa=
n title=3D"Pages: 130=E2=80=93135">:=E2=80=8A130=E2=80=93135=E2=80=8A</span=
></sup> The SI Brochure has specific rules for writing them.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-SIBrochure_16-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure-16"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 130=E2=80=93135">:=E2=
=80=8A130=E2=80=93135=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>In addition, the SI Brochure provides style conventions for among ot=
her aspects of displaying quantities units: the quantity symbols, formattin=
g of numbers and the decimal marker, expressing measurement uncertainty, mu=
ltiplication and division of quantity symbols, and the use of pure numbers =
and various angles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-23" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Unit=
s#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><s=
pan title=3D"Page: 147">:=E2=80=8A147=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>In the United States, the guideline produced by the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Institute_of_Standards_and_Technology" ti=
tle=3D"National Institute of Standards and Technology">National Institute o=
f Standards and Technology</a> (NIST)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST811_17-1" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Syst=
em_of_Units#cite_note-NIST811-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap=
"><span title=3D"Page: 37">:=E2=80=8A37=E2=80=8A</span></sup> clarifies lan=
guage-specific details for American English that were left unclear by the S=
I Brochure, but is otherwise identical to the SI Brochure.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-NISTInterprepation_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-NISTInterprepation-21=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> For example, since 1979, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Litre" title=3D"Litre">litre</a> may exceptionally be written usin=
g either an uppercase&nbsp;"L" or a lowercase&nbsp;"l", a decision prompted=
 by the similarity of the lowercase letter&nbsp;"l" to the numeral&nbsp;"1"=
, especially with certain typefaces or English-style handwriting. NIST reco=
mmends that within the United States, "L" be used rather than&nbsp;"l".<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-NIST811_17-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-NIST811-17"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Realisation_of_units">Reali=
sation of units <span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Realisation"></span></h2><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInternational_System_=
of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Realisa=
tion of units"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Realisation_(metrolo=
gy)" title=3D"Realisation (metrology)">Realisation (metrology)</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Silicon_sphere_for_Avogadro_project.jpg" clas=
s=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedi=
a/commons/thumb/4/41/Silicon_sphere_for_Avogadro_project.jpg/250px-Silicon_=
sphere_for_Avogadro_project.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D=
"260" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"631" data-file-height=3D=
"863"></a><figcaption>Silicon sphere for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Avogadro_project" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Avogadro projec=
t">Avogadro project</a> used for measuring the Avogadro constant to a relat=
ive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_uncertainty" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Standard uncertainty">standard uncertainty</a> of <s=
pan class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6992200000000000000=E2=99=A0"=
></span>2<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</sp=
an>10<sup>=E2=88=928</sup></span> or less, held by <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Achim_Leistner" title=3D"Achim Leistner">Achim Leistner</a=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></figcapt=
ion></figure>
<p>Metrologists carefully distinguish between the definition of a unit and =
its realisation. The SI units are defined by declaring that seven <i>defini=
ng constants</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-24" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#c=
ite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span=
 title=3D"Pages: 125=E2=80=93129">:=E2=80=8A125=E2=80=93129=E2=80=8A</span>=
</sup> have certain exact numerical values when expressed in terms of their=
 SI units. The realisation of the definition of a unit is the procedure by =
which the definition may be used to establish the value and associated unce=
rtainty of a quantity of the same kind as the unit.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBr=
ochure9thEd_1-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 135">:=E2=80=8A135=E2=
=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>For each base unit the BIPM publishes a <span title=3D"French-langua=
ge text"><i lang=3D"fr">mises en pratique</i></span>, (<a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_language" title=3D"French language">French</a> =
for 'putting into practice; implementation',<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST_mise_e=
n_pratique_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-NIST_mise_en_pratique-23"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>) describing the current best practical realisations of the unit.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-MisesEnPratique_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-MisesEnPrati=
que-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> The separation of the defining constants from the defin=
itions of units means that improved measurements can be developed leading t=
o changes in the <span title=3D"French-language text"><i lang=3D"fr">mises =
en pratique</i></span> as science and technology develop, without having to=
 revise the definitions.
</p><p>The published <span title=3D"French-language text"><i lang=3D"fr">mi=
se en pratique</i></span> is not the only way in which a base unit can be d=
etermined: the SI Brochure states that "any method consistent with the laws=
 of physics could be used to realise any SI unit".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBro=
chure_16-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
ternational_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure-16"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=
=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 111">:=E2=80=8A111=E2=80=8A</spa=
n></sup> Various consultative committees of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/CIPM" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"CIPM">CIPM</a> decided i=
n 2016 that more than one <span title=3D"French-language text"><i lang=3D"f=
r">mise en pratique</i></span> would be developed for determining the value=
 of each unit.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-25"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> These methods include the following:
</p>
<ul><li>At least three separate experiments be carried out yielding values =
having a relative <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_uncerta=
inty" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Standard uncertainty">standard uncerta=
inty</a> in the determination of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Kilogram" title=3D"Kilogram">kilogram</a> of no more than <span class=3D=
"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6992500000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>5<sp=
an style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=
=E2=88=928</sup></span> and at least one of these values should be better t=
han <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6992200000000000000=E2=
=99=A0"></span>2<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=
=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=928</sup></span>. Both the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Kibble_balance" title=3D"Kibble balance">Kibble balance</a=
> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avogadro_project" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Avogadro project">Avogadro project</a> should be =
included in the experiments and any differences between these be reconciled=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The definition of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelvin" =
title=3D"Kelvin">kelvin</a> measured with a relative uncertainty of the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boltzmann_constant" title=3D"Boltzman=
n constant">Boltzmann constant</a> derived from two fundamentally different=
 methods such as acoustic gas <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ther=
mometry" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Thermometry">thermometry</a> and di=
electric constant gas thermometry be better than one part in <span class=3D=
"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6994100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<s=
up>=E2=88=926</sup></span> and that these values be corroborated by other m=
easurements.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-28"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Organisational_status">Orga=
nisational status</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DInternational_System_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Organisational status"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Metric_and_imperial_systems_(2019).svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/0/08/Metric_and_imperial_systems_%282019%29.svg/330px-Metric=
_and_imperial_systems_%282019%29.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"330" =
height=3D"168" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2754" data-file=
-height=3D"1398"></a><figcaption>Countries using the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_system" title=3D"Metric system">metric</a> (SI), =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_units" title=3D"Imperial =
units">imperial</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_custom=
ary" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"US customary">US customary</a> systems =
as of 2019</figcaption></figure>
<p>The International System of Units, or SI,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9=
thEd_1-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Int=
ernational_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup clas=
s=3D"reference nowrap">:=E2=80=8A<span title=3D"Page: 123
Quotation: &quot;... since its establishment in 1960, the International Sys=
tem of Units has always been referred to as &quot;the SI&quot; in its short=
ened form.&quot;" class=3D"tooltip tooltip-dashed" style=3D"border-bottom: =
1px dashed;">123</span>=E2=80=8A</sup> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Decimal" title=3D"Decimal">decimal</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_system" title=3D"Metric system">metric</a> <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_units" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"System of units">system of units</a> established in 1960 and period=
ically updated since then. The SI has an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Metrication" title=3D"Metrication">official status</a> in most count=
ries, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metrication_in_the=
_United_States" title=3D"Metrication in the United States">the United State=
s</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metrication_in_Canada" titl=
e=3D"Metrication in Canada">Canada</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Metrication_in_the_United_Kingdom" title=3D"Metrication in the Un=
ited Kingdom">the United Kingdom</a>, although these three countries are am=
ong the handful of nations that, to various degrees, also continue to use t=
heir customary systems. Nevertheless, with this nearly universal level of a=
cceptance, the SI "has been used around the world as the preferred system o=
f units, the basic language for science, technology, industry, and trade."<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochu=
re9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: =
123, 126">:=E2=80=8A123,=E2=80=8A126=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>The only other types of measurement system that still have widesprea=
d use across the world are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imp=
erial_and_US_customary_measurement_systems" title=3D"Imperial and US custom=
ary measurement systems">imperial and US customary measurement systems</a>.=
 The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_yard_and_pound"=
 title=3D"International yard and pound">international yard and pound</a> ar=
e defined in terms of the SI.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Standards1959_29-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Syste=
m_of_Units#cite_note-Standards1959-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"International_System_of_Qua=
ntities">International System of Quantities</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInternational_System_of_Units&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: International System of Quant=
ities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System=
_of_Quantities" title=3D"International System of Quantities">International =
System of Quantities</a></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_quantity" title=3D=
"Physical quantity">quantities</a> and equations that provide the context i=
n which the SI units are defined are now referred to as the <i><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Quantities" title=3D"I=
nternational System of Quantities">International System of Quantities</a></=
i> (ISQ).
The ISQ is based on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_quant=
ity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Base quantity">base quantities</a> unde=
rlying each of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_base_units" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI base units">seven base units of the SI</a=
>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derived_quantity" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Derived quantity">Derived quantities</a>, such as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"Area">area</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pressure" title=3D"Pressure">pressure</a>, a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_resistance" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Electrical resistance">electrical resistance</a>, fo=
llow from these base quantities by clear, non-contradictory equations. The =
ISQ defines the quantities that are measured with the SI units.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
ternational_System_of_Units#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The ISQ is formalised=
, in part, in the international standard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/ISO/IEC_80000" title=3D"ISO/IEC 80000">ISO/IEC 80000</a>, which was =
completed in 2009 with the publication of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/ISO_80000-1" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"ISO 80000-1">ISO 80000-=
1</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and=
 has largely been revised in 2019=E2=80=932020.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Syst=
em_of_Units#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Controlling_authority">Cont=
rolling authority</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DInternational_System_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Controlling authority"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Conference_=
on_Weights_and_Measures" title=3D"General Conference on Weights and Measure=
s">General Conference on Weights and Measures</a> and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Bureau_of_Weights_and_Measures" title=3D"=
International Bureau of Weights and Measures">International Bureau of Weigh=
ts and Measures</a></div>
<p>The SI is regulated and continually developed by three international org=
anisations that were established in 1875 under the terms of the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre_Convention" title=3D"Metre Convention">=
Metre Convention</a>. They are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/General_Conference_on_Weights_and_Measures" title=3D"General Conference on=
 Weights and Measures">General Conference on Weights and Measures</a> (CGPM=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-French_CGPM_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-French_CGPM=
-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>c<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FR_Interpretation_of_the_SI_34-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Syst=
em_of_Units#cite_note-FR_Interpretation_of_the_SI-34"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the Inter=
national Committee for Weights and Measures (CIPM<sup id=3D"cite_ref-French=
_CIPM_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
ternational_System_of_Units#cite_note-French_CIPM-35"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>d<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>), and the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Bureau_of_Weights_an=
d_Measures" title=3D"International Bureau of Weights and Measures">Internat=
ional Bureau of Weights and Measures</a> (BIPM<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BIPM_from=
_French_36-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
International_System_of_Units#cite_note-BIPM_from_French-36"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>e<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>).
<span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"SI_Brochure"></span>All the decisions and reco=
mmendations concerning units are collected in a brochure called <i>The Inte=
rnational System of Units (SI)</i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure9thEd_1-28=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internationa=
l_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure9thEd-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which is publishe=
d in French and English by the BIPM and periodically updated. The writing a=
nd maintenance of the brochure is carried out by one of the committees of t=
he CIPM. The definitions of the terms "quantity", "unit", "dimension", etc.=
 that are used in the <i>SI Brochure</i> are those given in the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_vocabulary_of_metrology" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International vocabulary of metrology">internatio=
nal vocabulary of metrology</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cit=
e_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> The brochure leaves some scope for local variations,=
 particularly regarding unit names and terms in different languages. For ex=
ample, the United States' <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National=
_Institute_of_Standards_and_Technology" title=3D"National Institute of Stan=
dards and Technology">National Institute of Standards and Technology</a> (N=
IST) has produced a version of the CGPM document (NIST SP 330), which clari=
fies usage for English-language publications that use <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_English" title=3D"American English">American E=
nglish</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST330_9-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-NIST3=
30-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
