<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CGS_system_of_units" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"CGS system of units">CGS system of units</a></d=
iv>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:US_National_Length_Meter.JPG"=
 class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wik=
ipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/US_National_Length_Meter.JPG/250px-US_National_Le=
ngth_Meter.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"214" class=3D"mw=
-file-element" data-file-width=3D"350" data-file-height=3D"300"></a><figcap=
tion>Closeup of the National Prototype Metre, serial number 27, allocated t=
o the United States</figcaption></figure>
<p>The concept of a system of units emerged a hundred years before the SI.
In the 1860s, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Clerk_Maxwell"=
 title=3D"James Clerk Maxwell">James Clerk Maxwell</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Thomson,_1st_Baron_Kelvin" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"William Thomson, 1st Baron Kelvin">William Thomson</a> (later =
Lord Kelvin), and others working under the auspices of the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Association_for_the_Advancement_of_Science=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"British Association for the Advancement of=
 Science">British Association for the Advancement of Science</a>, building =
on previous work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Gauss" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Carl Gauss">Carl Gauss</a>, developed the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centimetre%E2%80%93gram%E2%80%93second=
_system_of_units" title=3D"Centimetre=E2=80=93gram=E2=80=93second system of=
 units">centimetre=E2=80=93gram=E2=80=93second system of units</a> or cgs s=
ystem in 1874. The systems formalised the concept of a collection of relate=
d units called a <i>coherent</i> system of units. In a coherent system, <i>=
base units</i> combine to define <i>derived units</i> without extra factors=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST330_9-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-NIST330-9"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 2">:=E2=80=8A2=
=E2=80=8A</span></sup> For example, using metre per second is coherent in a=
 system that uses metre for length and second for time, but kilometre per h=
our is not coherent. The principle of coherence was successfully used to de=
fine a number of units of measure based on the CGS, including the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erg" title=3D"Erg">erg</a> for <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Energy" title=3D"Energy">energy</a>, the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dyne" title=3D"Dyne">dyne</a> for <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Force" title=3D"Force">force</a>, the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barye" title=3D"Barye">barye</a> =
for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pressure" title=3D"Pressure">p=
ressure</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poise_(unit)" tit=
le=3D"Poise (unit)">poise</a> for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Dynamic_viscosity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dynamic viscosity">dynami=
c viscosity</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stokes_(un=
it)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Stokes (unit)">stokes</a> for <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kinematic_viscosity" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Kinematic viscosity">kinematic viscosity</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-BIPMCentenary_39-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-BIPMCentenary-39"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Metre_Convention">Metre Con=
vention</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInte=
rnational_System_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit=
 section: Metre Convention"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre_Convention" t=
itle=3D"Metre Convention">Metre Convention</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/MKS_system_of_units" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"MKS sy=
stem of units">MKS system of units</a></div>
<p>A French-inspired initiative for international cooperation in <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metrology" title=3D"Metrology">metrology</a>=
 led to the signing in 1875 of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Metre_Convention" title=3D"Metre Convention">Metre Convention</a>, also ca=
lled Treaty of the Metre, by 17 nations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_U=
nits#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>f<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Alder_41-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Unit=
s#cite_note-Alder-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span titl=
e=3D"Pages: 353=E2=80=93354">:=E2=80=8A353=E2=80=93354=E2=80=8A</span></sup=
> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Conference_on_Weight=
s_and_Measures" title=3D"General Conference on Weights and Measures">Genera=
l Conference on Weights and Measures</a> (French: <span title=3D"French-lan=
guage text"><i lang=3D"fr">Conf=C3=A9rence g=C3=A9n=C3=A9rale des poids et =
mesures</i></span> =E2=80=93 CGPM), which was established by the Metre Conv=
ention,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-BIPMCentenary_39-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-B=
IPMCentenary-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> brought together many international organisati=
ons to establish the definitions and standards of a new system and to stand=
ardise the rules for writing and presenting measurements.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-Giunta_42-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-Giunta-42"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=
=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 37">:=E2=80=8A37=E2=80=8A</span>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Ini=
tially the convention only covered standards for the metre and the kilogram=
. This became the foundation of the MKS system of units.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-NIST330_9-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
International_System_of_Units#cite_note-NIST330-9"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"=
reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 2">:=E2=80=8A2=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Giovanni_Giorgi_and_the_pro=
blem_of_electrical_units">Giovanni Giorgi and the problem of electrical uni=
ts</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInternati=
onal_System_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Giovanni Giorgi and the problem of electrical units"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>At the close of the 19th century three different systems of units of mea=
sure existed for electrical measurements: a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/CGS-based_system_for_electrostatic_units" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"CGS-based system for electrostatic units">CGS-based system for elec=
trostatic units</a>, also known as the Gaussian or ESU system, a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CGS-based_system_for_electromechanical_units=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"CGS-based system for electromechanical uni=
ts">CGS-based system for electromechanical units</a> (EMU), and an Internat=
ional system based on units defined by the Metre Convention<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intern=
ational_System_of_Units#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> for electrical distributi=
on systems. Attempts to resolve the electrical units in terms of length, ma=
ss, and time using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensional_ana=
lysis" title=3D"Dimensional analysis">dimensional analysis</a> was beset wi=
th difficulties =E2=80=93 the dimensions depended on whether one used the E=
SU or EMU systems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Maxwell2_45-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_n=
ote-Maxwell2-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This anomaly was resolved in 1901 when <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giovanni_Giorgi" title=3D"Giovanni Giorgi=
">Giovanni Giorgi</a> published a paper in which he advocated using a fourt=
h base unit alongside the existing three base units. The fourth unit could =
be chosen to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_current" =
title=3D"Electric current">electric current</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Voltage" title=3D"Voltage">voltage</a>, or <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_resistance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Electrical resistance">electrical resistance</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-IE=
CGiorgi_46-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
International_System_of_Units#cite_note-IECGiorgi-46"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Electric current with named unit 'ampere' was chosen as the base uni=
t, and the other electrical quantities derived from it according to the law=
s of physics. When combined with the MKS the new system, known as MKSA, was=
 approved in 1946.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST330_9-7" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_not=
e-NIST330-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"9th_CGPM,_the_precursor_to_=
SI"><span id=3D"9th_CGPM.2C_the_precursor_to_SI"></span>9th CGPM, the precu=
rsor to SI</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DI=
nternational_System_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"E=
dit section: 9th CGPM, the precursor to SI"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In 1948, the 9th CGPM commissioned a study to assess the measurement nee=
ds of the scientific, technical, and educational communities and "to make r=
ecommendations for a single practical system of units of measurement, suita=
ble for adoption by all countries adhering to the Metre Convention".<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This working doc=
ument was <i>Practical system of units of measurement</i>. Based on this st=
udy, the 10th CGPM in 1954 defined an international system derived from six=
 base units: the metre, kilogram, second, ampere, degree Kelvin, and candel=
a.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The 9th CGPM also approved the first formal recommendation for the w=
riting of symbols in the metric system when the basis of the rules as they =
are now known was laid down.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_no=
te-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> These rules were subsequently extended and now cover uni=
t symbols and names, prefix symbols and names, how quantity symbols should =
be written and used, and how the values of quantities should be expressed.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure_16-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure-16=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Pages: 104, 130=
">:=E2=80=8A104,=E2=80=8A130=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Birth_of_the_SI">Birth of t=
he SI</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIntern=
ational_System_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Birth of the SI"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The 10th CGPM in 1954 resolved to create an international system of unit=
s<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Giunta_42-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-Giunta-42"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 41">:=E2=80=8A4=
1=E2=80=8A</span></sup> and in 1960, the 11th CGPM adopted the <i>Internati=
onal System of Units</i>, abbreviated SI from the French name <span title=
=3D"French-language text"><i lang=3D"fr">Le Syst=C3=A8me international d'un=
it=C3=A9s</i></span>, which included a specification for units of measureme=
nt.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure_16-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochur=
e-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 110">=
:=E2=80=8A110=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Bureau_of=
_Weights_and_Measures" title=3D"International Bureau of Weights and Measure=
s">International Bureau of Weights and Measures</a> (BIPM) has described SI=
 as "the modern form of metric system".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure_16-6"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International=
_System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"referenc=
e nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 95">:=E2=80=8A95=E2=80=8A</span></sup> In 19=
68, the unit "degree Kelvin" was renamed "kelvin". In 1971 the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mole_(unit)" title=3D"Mole (unit)">mole</a> be=
came the seventh base unit of the SI.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST330_9-8" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Syste=
m_of_Units#cite_note-NIST330-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><=
span title=3D"Page: 2">:=E2=80=8A2=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"2019_redefinition">2019 red=
efinition</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIn=
ternational_System_of_Units&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Ed=
it section: 2019 redefinition"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
