=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>=E2=88=923</sup>&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup></span></span>.=
</figcaption></figure>
<p>Many non-SI units continue to be used in the scientific, technical, and =
commercial literature. Some units are deeply embedded in history and cultur=
e, and their use has not been entirely replaced by their SI alternatives. T=
he CIPM recognised and acknowledged such traditions by compiling a list of =
non-SI units accepted for use with SI,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIBrochure_16-7" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_=
System_of_Units#cite_note-SIBrochure-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> including the hour, mi=
nute, degree of angle, litre, and decibel.
</p><p>This is a list of units that are not defined as part of the <a class=
=3D"mw-selflink selflink">International System of Units</a> (<a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI">SI</a>) b=
ut are otherwise mentioned in the SI Brochure,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-bipm_55-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internationa=
l_System_of_Units#cite_note-bipm-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> listed as being accepted f=
or use alongside SI units, or for explanatory purposes.
</p>
