<p>The SI prefixes can be used with several of these units, but not, for ex=
ample, with the non-SI units of time.=20
Others, in order to be converted to the corresponding SI unit, require conv=
ersion factors that are not powers of ten. Some common examples of such uni=
ts are the customary units of time, namely the minute (conversion factor of=
 <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7000100000000000000=E2=99=
=A0"></span>60&nbsp;s/min</span>, since <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=
=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7001600000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1=
&nbsp;min</span> =3D <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"700160=
0000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>60&nbsp;s</span></span>), the hour (<span cl=
ass=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7003360000000000000=E2=99=A0"></spa=
n>3600&nbsp;s</span>), and the day (<span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-=
value=3D"7004864000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>86<span style=3D"margin-left:=
.25em;">400</span>&nbsp;s</span>); the degree (for measuring plane angles, =
